00:47:11.530 --> 00:47:16.920
comment on is how we use the two
phase regime in purification.

00:47:16.920 --> 00:47:22.300
Much of what we know about
purification requires that we go

00:47:22.300 --> 00:47:41.033
into a two-phase regime.
Because the thing that happens in a

00:47:07.500 --> 00:47:12.500
two phase regime is two phase region
implies compositional

00:47:12.500 --> 00:47:23.000
differentiation.

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:49.160
For example, here is the phase
diagram. For one time,

00:47:49.160 --> 00:47:55.330
I am going to go to liquid vapor.
This is the liquid vapor phase

00:47:55.330 --> 00:48:01.490
diagram of ethyl alcohol and water.
We know that water boils at 100

00:48:01.490 --> 00:48:07.660
degrees C. This is normal boiling
point. And ethyl alcohol boils at

00:48:07.660 --> 00:48:13.830
78.5 degrees C.
And they are both polar liquids.

00:48:13.830 --> 00:48:31.326
Ethyl alcohol is a little bit more
elongated than water.

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:24.280
It is very nearly an isomorphous
phase diagram.

00:48:24.280 --> 00:48:28.570
There is a tiny little dip but,
by and large, it is an isomorphous

00:48:28.570 --> 00:48:32.850
phase diagram.
Alcohol and water,

00:48:32.850 --> 00:48:37.140
miscible in all proportions in the
vapor, obviously.

00:48:37.140 --> 00:48:41.420
And this is the liquid.
This is the two phase liquid plus

00:48:41.420 --> 00:48:45.710
vapor regime. Let's say you have
some wine and it is 10% alcohol.

00:48:45.710 --> 00:49:05.486
What do you do? You heat the wine
up to this two phase regime.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:56.440
And now, in the two phase regime,
tie line. What do you note? You

00:48:56.440 --> 00:49:02.880
note that the alcohol content of the
vapor is much higher than the

00:49:02.880 --> 00:49:09.330
alcohol content of the liquid.
What we can do is condense the

00:49:09.330 --> 00:49:15.770
vapor, which puts us down here,
and now reheat. Condense. Reheat.

00:49:15.770 --> 00:49:21.330
Condense.
And, by doing so,

00:49:21.330 --> 00:49:25.990
we can raise the alcohol content.
Or, in some cases, this could be

00:49:25.990 --> 00:49:30.660
the way you purify for the liquid.
It doesn't matter. You either want

00:49:30.660 --> 00:49:35.330
the condensate or you want what was
the base from which you took the

00:49:35.330 --> 00:49:39.990
condensate. And this is used over
and over again.

00:49:39.990 --> 00:49:44.660
It is used in the solid-state to
purify metals.

00:49:44.660 --> 00:49:49.330
Look up here on the slide.
Suppose I have a solution that

00:49:49.330 --> 00:50:07.460
consists of, over here
of, say, 60% nickel.

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:38.000
It is all liquid.
Drop it down into this two phase

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:42.000
regime. The solid that comes out
has very much less gold in it.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:46.000
That means that the liquid behind,
the last liquid to solidify is going

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:50.000
to have more gold in it than the
bulk that I started with.

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:54.000
I can keep taking that fraction by
moving into a regime where the

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:58.000
composition splits.
And I either want the high fraction

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:22.380
or the low fraction.
This is the principle by which,

00:50:22.380 --> 00:50:27.150
in fact, the computer-grade silicon
is made. We start with beach sand.

00:50:27.150 --> 00:50:31.920
We upgrade to something that has to
be about four or five nines silicon

00:50:31.920 --> 00:50:36.690
for single crystal growth.
How do we go from something that is

00:50:36.690 --> 00:50:41.450
about 98% silicon,
2% impurities to such a high degree

00:50:41.450 --> 00:50:46.220
of purification?
By dropping repeatedly into the two

00:50:46.220 --> 00:51:04.506
phase regime and pulling
out the pure fraction.

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:35.500
The key here is compositional
differentiation,

00:50:35.500 --> 00:50:40.000
which then allows you to distill.
You start with 10%, you end up 40%,

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:44.500
you go from wine and end up with
brandy or cognac.

